Welcome to enother episode of werewolf gaming ;) hope you enjoyed this video.
Make sure you like, comment and share my videos if you enjoy them, helps out alot. 
Thanks wolves and wolfettes.

This channel has been set up for fun, ive gamed for 18+ years on all platforms
my favourite being Playstation followed by Nintendo. So have decided to bring my gaming
knowledge and enjoyment to youtube. I have several goals for my youtube channel that i hope to achieve
by 2016. 

I would like to build a pack of loyal wolves that can play together and chat everyday.
I want this to be a place that anyone can come to and fit in, a place where you can get
away from your troubles or just the stress of everyday life.
I also aim to be unique, many people copy big youtubers and have no identity, where as i do.
You come to my channel and even if you hate my guts you'll always remember that werewolf
in the corner ;).

And as im asked a few times. My name is David and im 22 almost 23 and i work
in a school, and depending how often i update this i could actually be 30 right now lol ;D

I usually upload 1-2 videos a day at around 6-7pm UK time

Thanks for reading all. The journey to 100,000 subscribers has begun, watch out youtube ;)

Some of my favourite Quotes

"For the strength of the Pack is the Wolf, and the strength of the Wolf is the Pack"

"Wolves may feature in our myths, our history, and our dreams, but they have their own future, their own loves, their own dreams to fulfill."
-Anthony Miles?

"We humans fear the beast within the wolf because we do not understand the beast within ourselves"
-Gerald Hausman?

“The price of being a sheep is boredom. The price of being a wolf is loneliness. Choose one or the other with great care.”
 -Hugh MacLeod

snippet.title: 🐹 KIDS PLAYING HAMSTER RUN-AROUND MAZE GAME 🐹
snippet.description:
9-year-old and a 5-year-old playing a toy hamster maze game.

Mind-blowing stuff.

We did it using the TOMY Run-around Hamster game which is available on Amazon UK at: https://amzn.to/3k4sJCe
( TOMY Hamster Race - Family Skill Game - Classic Labyrinth Game - High Quality Kids Toys for Age 5 and up )

Game play:

* Each player chooses one side of the box. You can only use the holes on your side of the box.
* The youngest player starts with Hammy the Hamster.
* Put a food ball through the top of the house and give it a spin!
* Send in the hamster through one of the holes to retrieve the food.
* The hamster will go inside and grab the food from the centre.
* If Hammy pops out of the holes without a food ball, send him back in!
* Any player can win the food. If Hammy brings you back a food ball pass Hammy to the next player.

How to win:

* When there are no more food balls at the base of the house the game is over.
* The player with the most food balls at the end wins!

Play Kart Kingdom at http://to.pbs.org/kidskartkingdom

Kart Kingdom is based on the system thinking curriculum. Any curriculum and educational resources for Kart Kingdom is developed with the help of our educational advisor, Arizona State University’s Center for Games and Impact.

Kart Kingdom helps players understand systems. A system refers to several different things that work together to create a whole, such as the pipes in the water system. Without the pipes, water cannot travel from the dam to your faucet at home. The idea of systems thinking is for an individual to understand what the system is and how it works. To be able to process using systems thinking is a crucial life skill for scientists, engineers, etc.

snippet.title: Turbo Kids - Game preview / gameplay
snippet.description:
Turbo Kids is a charming and fun little racer that puts you in control of said kids who are, of course, turbo.  You'll jump chasms, pelt other kids with snowballs (which turn them to ice), and collect points while trying to get to first.

Turbo Kids looks simple and kiddie, and while it may indeed be on the cartoony side, doesn't mean that it's not a fun game.  Behind the name and the simple graphics is a solid platformer.

As aforementioned, the graphics are cartoony and kiddie.  This is not to mean that they're bad though, on the contrary, the graphical style adds a lot to the game by giving it a special charm and aesthetic.  The sprites of the turbo kids are cute and tiny little things that animate very nicely.  Granted, they may only have a few frames of animation each, but coupled with the minimalist design of the levels, it works very well.  While it's a racer, and while you may indeed be racing for first while trying to knock out the competition, the graphical style makes the game feel more relaxed and easy-going.  This is definitely a plus, as without such, you may very well get rather frustrated by the number of times you'll fall behind in the race, or literally fall into a bottomless chasm.

The audio is another high point of the game, with the voice-overs easily being of professional quality, and definitely not something you'd expect from such a cutesy looking game.  The music is also great, giving the game a feel reminiscent of old-school games without having to resort to chiptunes.  In addition to the music and voice, the sound effects are also of good quality.  Granted, there aren't too many things in the game that'll have sound effects, but those that do work very well.

The controls are simple enough, you hit x to shoot and c to jump.  Pretty much everything else is controlled by the computer, so the only things you really have to worry about are the timing of your jumps, and hitting your opponents.  This control scheme can be a bit troublesome to get used to at first, especially when you want to go back to pick up some points you missed, but for the most part it works well and is easy enough to get used to.

As can be guessed, the game is a platformer/racer that puts you in control of a little blue kid.  The little blue kid is racing against other kids, but unlike him, they're red.  You race from point A to point B, jumping across chasms, hitting accelerators to speed ahead of the competition, and jumping onto boosters to enhance your jumps.  It's a simple game, true, but it plays well and will surely capture your attention.  Unfortunately, it's a bit on the short side.

All in all, Turbo Kids is a fun, short, little game.  It has solid gameplay, and while short, will definitely keep your entertained while it lasts.

The sprites of the turbo kids are cute and tiny little things that animate very nicely.  Granted, they may only have a few frames of animation each, but coupled with the minimalist design of the levels, it works very well.  While it's a racer, and while you may indeed be racing for first while trying to knock out the competition, the graphical style makes the game feel more relaxed and easy-going.  This is definitely a plus, as without such, you may very well get rather frustrated by the number of times you'll fall behind in the race, or literally fall into a bottomless chasm.

The audio is another high point of the game, with the voice-overs easily being of professional quality, and definitely not something you'd expect from such a cutesy looking game.  The music is also great, giving the game a feel reminiscent of old-school games without having to resort to chiptunes.  In addition to the music and voice, the sound effects are also of good quality.  Granted, there aren't too many things in the game that'll have sound effects, but those that do work very well.

The controls are simple enough, you hit x to shoot and c to jump.  Pretty much everything else is controlled by the computer, so the only things you really have to worry about are the timing of your jumps, and hitting your opponents.  This control scheme can be a bit troublesome to get used to at first, especially when you want to go back to pick up some points you missed, but for the most part it works well and is easy enough to get used to.

As can be guessed, the game is a platformer/racer that puts you in control of a little blue kid.  The little blue kid is racing against other kids, but unlike him, they're red.  You race from point A to point B, jumping across chasms, hitting accelerators to speed ahead of the competition, and jumping onto boosters to enhance your jumps.  It's a simple game, true, but it plays well and will surely capture your attention.  Unfortunately, it's a bit on the short side.

All in all, Turbo Kids is a fun, short, little game.  It has solid gameplay, and while short, will definitely keep your entertained while it lasts.
